# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: integrated-circuit
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:integrated-circuit/1-bit-computing] In computer architecture, **1-bit** integers or other data units are those that are 1 bit (1/8 octet) wide.
[src:integrated-circuit/1-bit-computing] Also, 1-bit central processing unit (CPU) and arithmetic logic unit (ALU) architectures are those that are based on registers of that size.
[src:integrated-circuit/1-bit-computing] There are no computers or microcontrollers of any kind that are exclusively 1-bit for all registers and address buses.
[src:integrated-circuit/1-bit-computing] A 1-bit register can only store two different values.
[src:integrated-circuit/1-bit-computing] This is very restrictive and therefore not enough for a program counter which, on modern systems, is implemented in an on-chip register, but is not implemented on-chip in some 1-bit systems.
[src:integrated-circuit/1-bit-computing] Opcodes for at least one 1-bit processor architecture were 4-bit and the address bus was 8-bit.
[src:integrated-circuit/1-bit-computing] While 1-bit computing is rarely used on its own today, 1-bit serial communication is still used in modern computers, even on machines with large internal buses.
[src:integrated-circuit/1-bit-computing] The first carbon nanotube computer from 2013 is a 1-bit one-instruction set computer (and has only 178 transistors; though it has only one instruction, it can emulate 20 MIPS instructions).
[src:integrated-circuit/1-bit-computing] A serial computer processes data a single bit at a time.
[src:integrated-circuit/1-bit-computing] For example, the PDP-8/S was a 12-bit computer using a 1-bit ALU, processing the 12 bits serially.
[src:integrated-circuit/1-bit-computing] An example of a 1-bit computer built from discrete logic SSI chips is the Wang 500 (1970/1971) calculator as well as the Wang 1200 (1971/1972) word processor series developed by Wang Laboratories.
[src:integrated-circuit/1-bit-computing] Other examples of 1-bit architectures are programmable logic controllers (PLCs), such as the 1969 PDP-14.
[src:integrated-circuit/1-bit-computing] These were often programmed in ladder logic or in instruction list (IL).
[src:integrated-circuit/1-bit-computing] An example of such a 1-bit architecture that was marketed as a CPU is the Motorola MC14500B Industrial Control Unit (ICU), introduced in 1977 and manufactured at least up into the mid 1990s.
[src:integrated-circuit/1-bit-computing] One of the computers known to be based on this CPU was the WDR 1-bit computer.
[src:integrated-circuit/1-bit-computing] This architecture was considered superior for programs making decisions rather than performing arithmetic computations, for ladder logic as well as for serial data processing.
[src:integrated-circuit/1-bit-computing] There are also several design studies for 1-bit architectures in academia, and corresponding 1-bit logic can also be found in programming.
[src:integrated-circuit/1-bit-computing] Several early massively parallel computers used 1-bit architectures for the processors as well.
[src:integrated-circuit/1-bit-computing] Examples include the May 1983 Goodyear MPP and the 1985 Connection Machine.
[src:integrated-circuit/1-bit-computing] By using a 1-bit architecture for the individual processors a very large array (e.g. the Connection Machine had 65,536 processors) could be constructed with the chip technology available at the time.
[src:integrated-circuit/1-bit-computing] In this case the slow computation of a 1-bit processor was traded off against the large number of processors.
[src:integrated-circuit/12-bit-computing] In computer architecture, **12-bit** integers, memory addresses, or other data units are those that are 12 bits (1.5 octets) wide.
[src:integrated-circuit/12-bit-computing] Also, 12-bit central processing unit (CPU) and arithmetic logic unit (ALU) architectures are those that are based on registers, address buses, or data buses of that size.
[src:integrated-circuit/12-bit-computing] Before the widespread adoption of ASCII in the late 1960s, six-bit character codes were common and a 12-bit word, which could hold two characters, was a convenient size.
[src:integrated-circuit/12-bit-computing] This also made it useful for storing a single decimal digit along with a sign.
[src:integrated-circuit/12-bit-computing] Possibly the best-known 12-bit CPUs are the PDP-8 and its descendants (such as the Intersil 6100 microprocessor), which were produced in various forms from August 1963 to mid-1990.
[src:integrated-circuit/12-bit-computing] Many analog to digital converters (ADCs) have a 12-bit resolution.
[src:integrated-circuit/12-bit-computing] Some PIC microcontrollers use a 12-bit instruction word but handle only 8-bit data.
[src:integrated-circuit/12-bit-computing] 12 binary digits, or 3 nibbles (a 'tribble'), have 4096 (10000 octal, 1000 hexadecimal) distinct combinations.
[src:integrated-circuit/12-bit-computing] Hence, a microprocessor with 12-bit memory addresses can directly access 4096 words (4 kW) of word-addressable memory.
[src:integrated-circuit/12-bit-computing] IBM System/360 instruction formats use a 12-bit displacement field which, added to the contents of a base register, can address 4096 bytes of memory in a region that begins at the address in the base register.
[src:integrated-circuit/128-bit-computing] In computer architecture, **128-bit** integers, memory addresses, or other data units are those that are 128 bits (16 octets) wide.
[src:integrated-circuit/128-bit-computing] Also, 128-bit central processing unit (CPU) and arithmetic logic unit (ALU) architectures are those that are based on registers, address buses, or data buses of that size.
[src:integrated-circuit/128-bit-computing] As of June 2026, there are no mainstream general-purpose processors built to operate on 128-bit *integers* or addresses, although a number of processors do have specialized ways to operate on 128-bit chunks of data as summarized in § Hardware.
[src:integrated-circuit/128-bit-computing] A processor with 128-bit byte addressing could directly address up to 2128 (over 3.40×1038) bytes, which would greatly exceed the total data captured, created, or replicated on Earth as of 2024, which has been estimated to be around 149 zettabytes (over 276 bytes).
[src:integrated-circuit/128-bit-computing] The range of integer values that can be stored in 128 bits depends on the integer representation used.
[src:integrated-circuit/128-bit-computing] Quadruple precision (128 bits) floating-point numbers can store 113-bit fixed-point numbers or integers accurately without losing precision (thus 64-bit integers in particular).
[src:integrated-circuit/128-bit-computing] Quadruple precision floats can also represent any position in the observable universe with at least micrometer precision.
[src:integrated-circuit/128-bit-computing] Decimal128 floating-point numbers can represent numbers with up to 34 significant digits.
[src:integrated-circuit/128-bit-computing] A 128-bit multicomparator was described by researchers in 1976.
[src:integrated-circuit/128-bit-computing] The IBM System/360 Model 85, and IBM System/370 and its successors, support 128-bit floating-point arithmetic.
[src:integrated-circuit/128-bit-computing] The Siemens 7.700 and 7.500 series mainframes and their successors support 128-bit floating-point arithmetic.
[src:integrated-circuit/128-bit-computing] Most modern CPUs feature single instruction, multiple data (SIMD) instruction sets (Streaming SIMD Extensions, AltiVec etc.) where 128-bit vector registers are used to store several smaller numbers, such as four 32-bit floating-point numbers.
[src:integrated-circuit/128-bit-computing] A single instruction can then operate on all these values in parallel.
[src:integrated-circuit/128-bit-computing] However, these processors do not operate on individual numbers that are 128 binary digits in length; only their vector registers have the size of 128 bits.
[src:integrated-circuit/128-bit-computing] The DEC VAX supported operations on 128-bit integer ('O' or octaword) and 128-bit floating-point ('H-float' or HFLOAT) datatypes.
[src:integrated-circuit/128-bit-computing] Support for such operations was an upgrade option rather than being a standard feature.
[src:integrated-circuit/128-bit-computing] Since the VAX's registers were 32 bits wide, a 128-bit operation used four consecutive registers or four longwords in memory.
[src:integrated-circuit/128-bit-computing] The ICL 2900 Series provided a 128-bit accumulator, and its instruction set included 128-bit floating-point and packed decimal arithmetic.
[src:integrated-circuit/128-bit-computing] A CPU with 128-bit multimedia extensions was designed by researchers in 1999.
[src:integrated-circuit/128-bit-computing] Among the sixth generation of video game consoles, the Dreamcast and the PlayStation 2 used the term *128-bit* in their marketing to describe their capability.
[src:integrated-circuit/128-bit-computing] The PlayStation 2's CPU had 128-bit SIMD capabilities.
[src:integrated-circuit/128-bit-computing] Neither console supported 128-bit addressing or 128-bit integer arithmetic.
[src:integrated-circuit/128-bit-computing] The RISC-V ISA specification from 2016 includes a reservation for a 128-bit version of the architecture, but the details remain undefined intentionally, because there is yet so little practical experience with such large word size.
[src:integrated-circuit/128-bit-computing] In the same way that compilers emulate, e.g., 64-bit integer arithmetic on architectures with register sizes less than 64 bits, some compilers also support 128-bit integer arithmetic.
[src:integrated-circuit/128-bit-computing] For example, the GCC C compiler 4.6 and later has a 128-bit integer type `__int128` for some architectures.
[src:integrated-circuit/128-bit-computing] GCC and compatible compilers signal the presence of 128-bit arithmetic when the macro `__SIZEOF_INT128__` is defined.
[src:integrated-circuit/128-bit-computing] For the C programming language, 128-bit support is optional, e.g. via the `int128_t` type, or it can be implemented by a compiler-specific extension.
[src:integrated-circuit/128-bit-computing] The Rust programming language has built-in support for 128-bit integers (originally via LLVM), which is implemented on all platforms.
[src:integrated-circuit/128-bit-computing] A 128-bit type provided by a C compiler can be available in Perl via the `Math::Int128` module.
[src:integrated-circuit/128-bit-computing] The C3 programming language provides an implementation of a 128-bit integer data type.
[src:integrated-circuit/16-bit-computing] In computer architecture, **16-bit** integers, memory addresses, or other data units are those that are 16 bits (2 octets) wide.
[src:integrated-circuit/16-bit-computing] Also, 16-bit central processing unit (CPU) and arithmetic logic unit (ALU) architectures are those that are based on registers, address buses, or data buses of that size.
[src:integrated-circuit/16-bit-computing] 16-bit microcomputers are microcomputers that use 16-bit microprocessors.
[src:integrated-circuit/16-bit-computing] A 16-bit register can store 216 different values.
[src:integrated-circuit/16-bit-computing] The range of integer values that can be stored in 16 bits depends on the integer representation used.
[src:integrated-circuit/16-bit-computing] With the two most common representations, the range is 0 through 65,535 (216 − 1) for representation as an (unsigned) binary number, and −32,768 (−1 × 215) through 32,767 (215 − 1) for representation as two's complement.
[src:integrated-circuit/16-bit-computing] Since 216 is 65,536, a processor with 16-bit memory addresses can directly access 64 KiB (65,536 bytes) of byte-addressable memory.
[src:integrated-circuit/16-bit-computing] If a system uses segmentation with 16-bit segment offsets, more can be accessed.
[src:integrated-circuit/16-bit-computing] 1951) was quite possibly the first-ever 16-bit computer.
[src:integrated-circuit/16-bit-computing] It had an unusual word size for the era; most systems used six-bit character code and used a word length of some multiple of 6-bits.
[src:integrated-circuit/16-bit-computing] This changed with the effort to introduce ASCII, which used a 7-bit code and naturally led to the use of an 8-bit multiple which could store a single ASCII character or two binary-coded decimal digits.
[src:integrated-circuit/16-bit-computing] The 16-bit word length thus became more common in the 1960s, especially on minicomputer systems.
[src:integrated-circuit/16-bit-computing] 1965–70) include the IBM 1130, the HP 2100, the Data General Nova, and the DEC PDP-11.
[src:integrated-circuit/16-bit-computing] Early 16-bit microprocessors, often modeled on one of the mini platforms, began to appear in the 1970s.
[src:integrated-circuit/16-bit-computing] Early single-chip 16-bit microprocessors (c.
[src:integrated-circuit/16-bit-computing] Other notable 16-bit processors include the Intel 8086, the Intel 80286, the WDC 65C816, and the Zilog Z8000.
[src:integrated-circuit/16-bit-computing] The Intel 8088 was binary compatible with the Intel 8086, and was 16-bit in that its registers were 16 bits wide, and arithmetic instructions could operate on 16-bit quantities, even though its external bus was 8 bits wide.
[src:integrated-circuit/16-bit-computing] 16-bit processors have been almost entirely supplanted in the personal computer industry, and are used less than 32-bit (or 8-bit) CPUs in embedded applications.
[src:integrated-circuit/16-bit-computing] The Motorola 68000 is sometimes called 16-bit because of the way it handles basic arithmetic.
[src:integrated-circuit/16-bit-computing] The instruction set was based on 32-bit numbers and the internal registers were 32 bits wide, so by common definitions, the 68000 is a 32-bit design.
[src:integrated-circuit/16-bit-computing] Internally, 32-bit arithmetic is performed using two 16-bit operations, and this leads to some descriptions of the system as 16-bit, or "16/32".
[src:integrated-circuit/16-bit-computing] Such solutions have a long history in the computer field, with various designs performing math even one bit at a time, known as "serial arithmetic", while most designs by the 1970s processed at least a few bits at a time.
[src:integrated-circuit/16-bit-computing] A common example is the Data General Nova, which was a 16-bit design that performed 16-bit math as a series of four 4-bit operations.
[src:integrated-circuit/16-bit-computing] 4-bits was the word size of a widely available single-chip ALU and thus allowed for inexpensive implementation.
[src:integrated-circuit/16-bit-computing] Using the definition being applied to the 68000, the Nova would be a 4-bit computer, or 4/16.
[src:integrated-circuit/16-bit-computing] Not long after the introduction of the Nova, a second version was introduced, the SuperNova, which included four of the 4-bit ALUs running in parallel to perform math 16 bits at a time and therefore offer higher performance.
[src:integrated-circuit/16-bit-computing] This was invisible to the user and the programs, which always used 16-bit instructions and data.
[src:integrated-circuit/16-bit-computing] In a similar fashion, later 68000-family members, starting with the Motorola 68020, had 32-bit ALUs.
[src:integrated-circuit/16-bit-computing] One may also see references to systems being, or not being, 16-bit based on some other measure.
[src:integrated-circuit/16-bit-computing] One common one is when the address space is not the same size of bits as the internal registers.
[src:integrated-circuit/16-bit-computing] Most 8-bit CPUs of the 1970s fall into this category; the MOS 6502, Intel 8080, Zilog Z80 and most others had 16-bit address space which provided 64 KiB of address space.
[src:integrated-circuit/16-bit-computing] This also meant address manipulation required two instruction cycles.
[src:integrated-circuit/16-bit-computing] For this reason, most processors had special 8-bit addressing modes, the zero page, improving speed.
[src:integrated-circuit/16-bit-computing] This sort of difference between internal register size and external address size remained in the 1980s, although often reversed, as memory costs of the era made a machine with 32-bit addressing, 2 or 4 GiB, a practical impossibility.
[src:integrated-circuit/16-bit-computing] For example, the 68000 exposed only 24 bits of addressing on the DIP, limiting it to a still huge (for the era) 16 MiB.
[src:integrated-circuit/16-bit-computing] A similar analysis applies to Intel's 80286 CPU replacement, called the 386SX, which is a 32-bit processor with 32-bit ALU and internal 32-bit data paths with a 16-bit external bus and 24-bit addressing of the processor it replaced.
[src:integrated-circuit/16-bit-computing] In the context of IBM PC compatible and Wintel platforms, a 16-bit application is any software written for MS-DOS, OS/2 1.x or early versions of Microsoft Windows which originally ran on the 16-bit Intel 8088 and Intel 80286 microprocessors.
[src:integrated-circuit/16-bit-computing] Such applications used a 20-bit or 24-bit segment or selector-offset address representation to extend the range of addressable memory locations beyond what was possible using only 16-bit addresses.
[src:integrated-circuit/16-bit-computing] Programs containing more than 216 bytes (65,536 bytes) of instructions and data therefore required special instructions to switch between their 64-kibibyte segments, increasing the complexity of programming 16-bit applications.
[src:integrated-circuit/16-bit-computing] Single chip 16-bit microcontrollers appeared around 1983 with the introduction of the Intel 8061.
[src:integrated-circuit/16-bit-computing] As of 2025, 16-bit microcontrollers cost well under a US dollar in 100 quantities, similar in price to legacy 8-bit.
[src:integrated-circuit/16-bit-computing] Even some 32-bit microcontrollers are priced under a US dollar.
[src:integrated-circuit/2-5d-integrated-circuit] A **2.5D integrated circuit** (**2.5D IC**) is an advanced packaging technique that combines multiple integrated circuit dies in a single package without stacking them into a three-dimensional integrated circuit (3D-IC) with through-silicon vias (TSVs).
[src:integrated-circuit/2-5d-integrated-circuit] The term "2.5D" originated when 3D-ICs with TSVs were quite new and still very difficult.
[src:integrated-circuit/2-5d-integrated-circuit] Chip designers realized that many of the advantages of 3D integration could be approximated by placing bare dies side by side on an interposer instead of stacking them vertically.
[src:integrated-circuit/2-5d-integrated-circuit] If the pitch is very fine and the interconnect very short, the assembly can be packaged as a single component with better size, weight, and power characteristics than a comparable 2D circuit board assembly.
[src:integrated-circuit/2-5d-integrated-circuit] This half-way 3D integration was facetiously named "2.5D" and the name stuck.
[src:integrated-circuit/2-5d-integrated-circuit] An interposer can support heterogeneous integration – that is, dies of different pitch, size, material, and process node.
[src:integrated-circuit/2-5d-integrated-circuit] Placing dies side by side instead of stacking them reduces heat buildup.
[src:integrated-circuit/2-5d-integrated-circuit] Upgrading or modifying a 2.5D assembly is as easy as swapping in a new component and revamping the interposer to suit; much faster and simpler than reworking an entire 3D-IC or System-on-Chip (SoC).
[src:integrated-circuit/2-5d-integrated-circuit] Some sophisticated 2.5D assemblies even incorporate TSVs and 3D components.
[src:integrated-circuit/2-5d-integrated-circuit] Several foundries now support 2.5D packaging.
[src:integrated-circuit/2-5d-integrated-circuit] The success of 2.5D assembly has given rise to "chiplets" – small, functional circuit blocks designed to be combined in mix-and-match fashion on interposers.
[src:integrated-circuit/2-5d-integrated-circuit] Several high-end products already take advantage of these LEGO-style chiplets; some experts predict the emergence of an industry-wide chiplet ecosystem.
[src:integrated-circuit/2-5d-integrated-circuit] Interposers can be larger than the reticle size which is the maximum area that can be projected by a photolithography scanner or stepper.
[src:integrated-circuit/2-5d-integrated-circuit] A 2.5D IC architecture is an intermediate solution between traditional 2D and advanced 3D architectures.
[src:integrated-circuit/2-5d-integrated-circuit] While a 2D architecture integrates all components on a single silicon die (SoC) and a 3D architecture stacks multiple dies vertically, the 2.5D approach involves placing multiple chiplets side-by-side on a silicon interposer within a single package.
[src:integrated-circuit/2-5d-integrated-circuit] The chiplets, which perform various functions, are bonded to the interposer, and the interconnection between them are routed on this interposer.
[src:integrated-circuit/2-5d-integrated-circuit] The interposer is then connected to the package substrate using silicon vias, which provide connections to peripheral hardware such as SRAM or DRAM.
[src:integrated-circuit/2-5d-integrated-circuit] The interposer, also known as a redistributed layer (RDL), is a key component in the physical design of chiplets.
[src:integrated-circuit/2-5d-integrated-circuit] It acts as an intermediate layer that facilitates communication between chiplets and provides interfaces for peripheral devices.
[src:integrated-circuit/2-5d-integrated-circuit] The design of the interposer and its wiring is crucial, as the routing of these wires can introduce additional latency and parasitic parameters that can affect overall performance and reliability.
[src:integrated-circuit/2-5d-integrated-circuit] In advanced packaging technologies like CoWoS, the interposer design method uses wiring within the interposer and through-silicon-via (TSV) technology to connect chiplets and establish connections to the packaging substrate.
[src:integrated-circuit/2-5d-integrated-circuit] Interposers can be made from different materials, including silicon, glass, and organics.
[src:integrated-circuit/2-5d-integrated-circuit] Silicon interposers are widely used due to their ability to achieve fine feature sizes with existing process technology, making them a cost-effective option.
[src:integrated-circuit/2-5d-integrated-circuit] Interposers use TSVs for communication between the chip and for connecting to the substrate.
[src:integrated-circuit/2-5d-integrated-circuit] A 10x100um TSV is sometimes used in an interposer with three or four metal layers on the probe side and a single copper RDL on the grind side.
[src:integrated-circuit/2-5d-integrated-circuit] There are several interposer technologies used in 2.5D ICs, each with its own set of trade-offs in terms of cost, performance, and complexity.
[src:integrated-circuit/2-5d-integrated-circuit] The interconnects in a 2.5D IC, including micro-bumps and underfill materials, play an important role in the enablement of high bandwidth and low power consumption.
[src:integrated-circuit/2-5d-integrated-circuit] The signal channels in a 2.5D integration consist of I/O drivers and receivers, I/O pads, micro-bumps, and chip-to-chip wires.
[src:integrated-circuit/2-5d-integrated-circuit] The wires are horizontally routed on an interconnect carrier, such as a bridge-chip, stitch-chip, or an interposer.
[src:integrated-circuit/2-5d-integrated-circuit] The use of smaller pads and micro-bumps in technologies like HIST (Heterogeneous Interconnect Stitching Technology) and interposers leads to smaller capacitance, which improves electrical performance.
[src:integrated-circuit/2-5d-integrated-circuit] For example, the total capacitance of a micro-bump and a pair of pads for HIST is about 18 times smaller than that of a bridge-chip because bridge-chip bumps also include organic package vias.
[src:integrated-circuit/2-5d-integrated-circuit] The reduced capacitance and shorter interconnects contribute to lower latency and energy consumption.
[src:integrated-circuit/2-5d-integrated-circuit] Furthermore, HIST and interposer-based solutions achieve the largest bandwidth-density (BWD) among 2.5D solutions due to the ultralow parasitics of micro-bumps and pads.
[src:integrated-circuit/2-5d-integrated-circuit] While 2.5D IC technology offers numerous advantages, it also presents several challenges and limitations that must be addressed.
[src:integrated-circuit/2-5d-integrated-circuit] 2.5D and 3D heterogeneous integration technologies are used in a variety of applications, particularly in high-performance computing (HPC), AI accelerators, high-end CPUs, and FPGAs.
[src:integrated-circuit/2-5d-integrated-circuit] The development of industry standards is crucial for the widespread adoption of 2.5D and 3D integration technologies.
[src:integrated-circuit/2-5d-integrated-circuit] Some future trends in 2.5D and 3D integration include the use of bridge technologies and co-packaged optics.
[src:integrated-circuit/2-5d-integrated-circuit] Intel's Co-EMIB combines Foveros and EMIB to provide 2.5D and 3D connectivity between dies in a package, achieving high interconnect density in both horizontal and vertical directions.
[src:integrated-circuit/2-5d-integrated-circuit] Another example is the omnidirectional interconnect (ODI), which can support high-bandwidth interconnects and direct power delivery using smaller TSVs and high-bandwidth interconnects.
[src:integrated-circuit/2-5d-integrated-circuit] Another approach is the use of photonic interconnects as a solution for high-bandwidth, low-power communication in 2.5D integrated systems.
[src:integrated-circuit/2-5d-integrated-circuit] In this case an Arrayed Waveguide Grating Router (AWGR) can be used, for example, as an optical switch fabric to construct a photonic Network-on-Chip (NoC) for interposer-based implementations.
[src:integrated-circuit/24-bit-computing] In computer architecture, **24-bit** integers, memory addresses, or other data units are those that are 24 bits (3 octets) wide.
[src:integrated-circuit/24-bit-computing] Also, 24-bit central processing unit (CPU) and arithmetic logic unit (ALU) architectures are those that are based on registers, address buses, or data buses of that size.
[src:integrated-circuit/24-bit-computing] Notable **24-bit** machines include the CDC 924 – a 24-bit version of the CDC 1604, CDC lower 3000 series, SDS 930 and SDS 940, the ICT 1900 series, the Elliott 4100 series, and the Datacraft minicomputers/Harris H series.
[src:integrated-circuit/24-bit-computing] The term SWORD is sometimes used to describe a 24-bit data type with the S prefix referring to sesqui.
[src:integrated-circuit/24-bit-computing] The range of unsigned integers that can be represented in 24 bits is 0 to 16,777,215 (FFFFFF16 in hexadecimal).
[src:integrated-circuit/24-bit-computing] The range of signed integers that can be represented in 24 bits is −8,388,608 to 8,388,607.
[src:integrated-circuit/24-bit-computing] The IV/70, was introduced by Four-Phase Systems in 1971.
[src:integrated-circuit/24-bit-computing] The IV/70 has an integer word size of 24 bits.
[src:integrated-circuit/24-bit-computing] Byte addressing is not supported directly but bytes are handled by instructions that pack three bytes per word.
[src:integrated-circuit/24-bit-computing] The IV/70 CPU is a 9-chip LSI microprocessor based on three AL4 8-bit slice register/ALUs.
[src:integrated-circuit/24-bit-computing] The IBM System/360, announced in 1964, was a popular computer system with 24-bit addressing and 32-bit general registers and arithmetic.
[src:integrated-circuit/24-bit-computing] The early 1980s saw the first popular personal computers, including the IBM PC/AT with an Intel 80286 processor using 24-bit addressing and 16-bit general registers and arithmetic, and the Apple Macintosh 128K with a Motorola 68000 processor featuring 24-bit addressing and 32-bit registers.
[src:integrated-circuit/24-bit-computing] Some late-1980s Apple computers such as the Macintosh SE/30 and Macintosh IIx retained some 24-bit code in their ROMs despite being advertised as 32-bit computers.
[src:integrated-circuit/24-bit-computing] As a result, these computers require the installation of the MODE32 memory manager to address more than 8Mb of RAM.
[src:integrated-circuit/24-bit-computing] The ARM1, supported 24-bit memory address, as it can access 16MiB memory.
[src:integrated-circuit/24-bit-computing] The eZ80 is a microprocessor and microcontroller family, with 24-bit registers and 24-bit linear addressing.
[src:integrated-circuit/24-bit-computing] It is binary compatible with the 8/16-bit Z80.
[src:integrated-circuit/24-bit-computing] Although eZ80 supports 24-bit adds, subtracts, and moves, most ALU operations are limited to 8-bit.
[src:integrated-circuit/24-bit-computing] The 65816 is a microprocessor and microcontroller family with 16-bit registers and 24-bit bank switched addressing.
[src:integrated-circuit/24-bit-computing] It is binary compatible with the 8-bit 6502.
[src:integrated-circuit/24-bit-computing] Several fixed-point digital signal processors have a 24-bit data bus, selected as the basic word length because it gave the system a reasonable precision for the processing audio (sound).
[src:integrated-circuit/24-bit-computing] In particular, the Motorola 56000 series has three parallel 24-bit data buses, one connected to each memory space: program memory, data memory X, and data memory Y.
[src:integrated-circuit/24-bit-computing] Engineering Research Associates (later merged into UNIVAC) designed a series of 24-bit drum memory machines including the Atlas, its commercial version the UNIVAC 1101, the ATHENA computer, the UNIVAC 1824 guidance computer, etc.
[src:integrated-circuit/24-bit-computing] Those designers selected a 24-bit word length because the Earth is roughly 40 million feet in diameter, and an intercontinental ballistic missile guidance computer needs to do the Earth-centered inertial navigation calculations to an accuracy of a few feet.
[src:integrated-circuit/24-bit-computing] OpenCL has a built-in intrinsic for multiplication (`mul24()`) with two 24-bit integers, returning a 32-bit result.
[src:integrated-circuit/24-bit-computing] It is typically much faster than a 32-bit multiplication.
[src:integrated-circuit/256-bit-computing] In computer architecture, **256-bit** integers, memory addresses, or other data units are those that are 256 bits (32 octets) wide.
[src:integrated-circuit/256-bit-computing] Also, 256-bit central processing unit (CPU) and arithmetic logic unit (ALU) architectures are those that are based on registers, address buses, or data buses of that size.
[src:integrated-circuit/256-bit-computing] There are currently no mainstream general-purpose processors built to operate on 256-bit integers or addresses, though a number of processors do operate on 256-bit data.
[src:integrated-circuit/256-bit-computing] A 256-bit quantity can store 2256 different values.
[src:integrated-circuit/256-bit-computing] The range of integer values that can be stored in 256 bits depends on the integer representation used.
[src:integrated-circuit/256-bit-computing] 256-bit processors could be used for addressing directly up to 2256 bytes.
[src:integrated-circuit/256-bit-computing] Already 2128 (for 128-bit addressing) would greatly exceed the total data stored on Earth as of 2018, which has been estimated to be around 33.3 ZBs (over 274 bytes).
[src:integrated-circuit/256-bit-computing] Xbox 360 was the first high-definition gaming console to utilize the ATI Technologies 256-bit GPU Xenos before the introduction of the current gaming consoles especially Nintendo Switch.
[src:integrated-circuit/256-bit-computing] Some buses on the newer System on a chip (e.g.
[src:integrated-circuit/256-bit-computing] Tegra developed by Nvidia) utilize 64-bit, 128-bit, 256-bit, or higher.
[src:integrated-circuit/256-bit-computing] CPUs feature SIMD instruction sets (Advanced Vector Extensions and the FMA instruction set etc.) where 256-bit vector registers are used to store several smaller numbers, such as eight 32-bit floating-point numbers, and a single instruction can operate on all these values in parallel.
[src:integrated-circuit/256-bit-computing] However, these processors do not operate on individual numbers that are 256 binary digits in length, only their registers have the size of 256-bits.
[src:integrated-circuit/256-bit-computing] Binary digits are found together in 128-bit collections.
[src:integrated-circuit/256-bit-computing] Modern GPU chips may operate data across a 256-bit memory bus (or possibly a 512-bit bus with HBM3).
[src:integrated-circuit/256-bit-computing] The Efficeon processor was Transmeta's second-generation 256-bit VLIW design which employed a software engine to convert code written for x86 processors to the native instruction set of the chip.
[src:integrated-circuit/256-bit-computing] The DARPA funded Data-Intensive Architecture (DIVA) system incorporated processor-in-memory (PIM) 5-stage pipelined 256-bit datapath, complete with register file and ALU blocks in a "WideWord" processor in 2002.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] An **integrated circuit** (**IC**), also known as a **microchip** or simply **chip**, is a compact assembly of electronic circuits formed from various electronic components, such as transistors, resistors, and capacitors, and their interconnections.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] These components are fabricated onto a thin, flat piece ("chip") of semiconductor material, most commonly silicon.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Integrated circuits are integral to a wide variety of electronic devices (including computers, smartphones, and televisions) performing functions such as data processing, control, and storage.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] They have transformed the field of electronics by enabling device miniaturization, improving performance, and reducing cost.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Compared to assemblies built from discrete components, integrated circuits are orders of magnitude smaller, faster, more energy-efficient, and less expensive, allowing for a very high transistor count.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Its capability for mass production, its high reliability, and the standardized, modular approach of integrated circuit design facilitated rapid replacement of designs using discrete transistors.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Today, ICs are present in virtually all electronic devices and have revolutionized modern technology.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Products such as computer processors, microcontrollers, digital signal processors, and embedded processing chips in home appliances are foundational to contemporary society due to their small size, low cost, and versatility.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Very-large-scale integration was made practical by technological advancements in semiconductor device fabrication.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Since their origins in the 1960s, the size, speed, and capacity of chips have progressed enormously, driven by technical advances that fit more and more transistors on chips of the same size – a modern chip may have many billions of transistors in an area the size of a human fingernail.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] These advances, roughly following Moore's law, make the computer chips of today possess millions of times the capacity and thousands of times the speed of the computer chips of the early 1970s.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] ICs have three main advantages over circuits constructed out of discrete components: size, cost and performance.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] The size and cost are low because the chips, with all their components, are printed as a unit by photolithography rather than being constructed one transistor at a time.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Furthermore, packaged ICs use much less material than discrete circuits.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Performance is high because the IC's components switch quickly and consume comparatively little power because of their small size and proximity.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] The main disadvantage of ICs is the high initial cost of designing them and the enormous capital cost of factory construction.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] This high initial cost means ICs are only commercially viable when high production volumes are anticipated.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] In its strict sense, the term refers to a single-piece circuit construction – originally called a *monolithic integrated circuit* – consisting of an entire circuit built on a single piece of silicon.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] In general usage, the designation "integrated circuit" can also apply to circuits that do not meet this strict definition, and which may be constructed using various technologies such as 3D IC, 2.5D IC, MCM, thin-film transistors, thick-film technology, or hybrid integrated circuits.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] This distinction in terminology is often relevant in debates on whether Moore's law remains applicable.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] A precursor concept to the IC was the development of small ceramic substrates, known as *micromodules*, each containing a single miniaturized electronic component.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] These modules could then be assembled and interconnected into a two- or three-dimensional compact grid.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] The idea, considered highly promising in 1957, was proposed to the U.S.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Army by Jack Kilby, leading to the short-lived Micromodule Program (similar in spirit to 1951's Project Tinkertoy).
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] However, as the project gained traction, Kilby devised a fundamentally new approach: the integrated circuit itself.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Newly employed by Texas Instruments, Kilby recorded his initial ideas concerning the integrated circuit in July 1958, successfully demonstrating the first working example of an integrated circuit on 12 September 1958.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] In his patent application of 6 February 1959, Kilby described his new device as "a body of semiconductor material ... wherein all the components of the electronic circuit are completely integrated".
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] The first customer for the new invention was the US Air Force.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Kilby won the 2000 Nobel Prize in physics for his part in the invention of the integrated circuit.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] However, Kilby's invention was not a true monolithic integrated circuit chip, as it relied on external gold-wire connections, making large-scale production impractical.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] About six months later, Robert Noyce at Fairchild Semiconductor developed the first practical monolithic IC chip.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] The monolithic integrated circuit chip was enabled by the inventions of the planar process by Jean Hoerni and of p–n junction isolation by Kurt Lehovec.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Hoerni's invention was built on Carl Frosch and Lincoln Derick's work on surface protection and passivation by silicon dioxide masking and predeposition, as well as Fuller, Ditzenberger's and others work on the diffusion of impurities into silicon.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Unlike Kilby's germanium-based design, Noyce's version was fabricated from silicon using the planar process by his colleague Jean Hoerni, which allowed reliable on-chip aluminum interconnections.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Modern IC chips are based on Noyce's monolithic design, rather than Kilby's early prototype.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] NASA's Apollo Program was the largest single consumer of integrated circuits between 1961 and 1965.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Transistor–transistor logic (TTL) was developed by James L.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] TTL became the dominant technology for digital integrated circuits during the 1970s to early 1980s.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Use of dozens of TTL integrated circuits was the standard method of construction for the processors of minicomputers and mainframe computers.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Computers such as IBM 360 mainframes, PDP-11 minicomputers and the desktop Datapoint 2200 were built from bipolar integrated circuits, either TTL or the faster emitter-coupled logic (ECL).
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Modern integrated circuits (ICs) are based on the metal–oxide–semiconductor field-effect transistor (MOSFET), forming MOS ICs.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] The MOSFET was developed at Bell Labs between 1955 and 1960, enabling the creation of high-density ICs.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Unlike bipolar transistors, which required additional steps for p–n junction isolation, MOSFETs could be easily isolated from one another without such measures.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] This advantage for integrated circuits was first highlighted by Dawon Kahng in 1961.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] The list of IEEE Milestones includes Kilby's first IC in 1958, Hoerni's planar process and Noyce's planar IC in 1959.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] The earliest experimental MOS IC to be fabricated was a 16-transistor chip built by Fred Heiman and Steven Hofstein at RCA in 1962.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] General Microelectronics later introduced the first commercial MOS integrated circuit in 1964, a 120-transistor shift register developed by Robert Norman.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] By 1964, MOS chips had reached higher transistor density and lower manufacturing costs than bipolar chips.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] MOS chips further increased in complexity at a rate predicted by Moore's law, leading to large-scale integration (LSI) with hundreds of transistors on a single MOS chip by the late 1960s.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] The application of MOS LSI chips to computing was the basis for the first microprocessors, as engineers began recognizing that a complete computer processor could be contained on a single MOS LSI chip.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] This led to the inventions of the microprocessor and the microcontroller by the early 1970s.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] During the early 1970s, MOS integrated circuit technology enabled the very large-scale integration (VLSI) of more than 10,000 transistors on a single chip.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] At first, MOS-based computers only made sense when high density was required, such as aerospace and pocket calculators.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Computers built entirely from TTL, such as the 1970 Datapoint 2200, were much faster and more powerful than single-chip MOS microprocessors, such as the 1972 Intel 8008, until the early 1980s.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Advances in IC technology, primarily smaller features and larger chips, have allowed the number of MOS transistors in an integrated circuit to double every two years, a trend known as Moore's law.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Moore originally stated it would double every year, but he went on to change the claim to every two years in 1975.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] This increased capacity has been used to decrease cost and increase functionality.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] In general, as the feature size shrinks, almost every aspect of an IC's operation improves.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] The cost per transistor and the switching power consumption per transistor goes down, while the memory capacity and speed go up, through the relationships defined by Dennard scaling (MOSFET scaling).
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Because speed, capacity, and power consumption gains are apparent to the end user, there is fierce competition among the manufacturers to use finer geometries.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Over the years, transistor sizes have decreased from tens of microns in the early 1970s to 10 nanometers in 2017 with a corresponding million-fold increase in transistors per unit area.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] As of 2016, typical chip areas range from a few square millimeters to around 600 mm2, with up to 25 million transistors per square millimeter.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] The expected shrinking of feature sizes and the needed progress in related areas was forecast for many years by the International Technology Roadmap for Semiconductors (ITRS).
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] The final ITRS was issued in 2016, and it is being replaced by the International Roadmap for Devices and Systems.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Initially, ICs were strictly electronic devices.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] The success of ICs has led to the integration of other technologies, in an attempt to obtain the same advantages of small size and low cost.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] These technologies include mechanical devices, optics, and sensors.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] As of 2018, the vast majority of all transistors are MOSFETs fabricated in a single layer on one side of a chip of silicon in a flat two-dimensional planar process.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Such techniques are collectively known as advanced packaging.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Advanced packaging is mainly divided into 2.5D and 3D packaging.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] 2.5D describes approaches such as multi-chip modules while 3D describes approaches where dies are stacked in one way or another, such as package on package and high bandwidth memory.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] All approaches involve 2 or more dies in a single package.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Alternatively, approaches such as 3D NAND stack multiple layers on a single die.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] A technique has been demonstrated to include microfluidic cooling on integrated circuits, to improve cooling performance as well as peltier thermoelectric coolers on solder bumps, or thermal solder bumps used exclusively for heat dissipation, used in flip-chip.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] The cost of designing and developing a complex integrated circuit is quite high, normally in the multiple tens of millions of dollars.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Therefore, it only makes economic sense to produce integrated circuit products with high production volume, so the non-recurring engineering (NRE) costs are spread across typically millions of production units.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Modern semiconductor chips have billions of components, and are far too complex to be designed by hand.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Software tools to help the designer are essential.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Electronic design automation (EDA), also referred to as electronic computer-aided design (ECAD), is a category of software tools for designing electronic systems, including integrated circuits.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] The tools work together in a design flow that engineers use to design, verify, and analyze entire semiconductor chips.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Some of the latest EDA tools use artificial intelligence (AI) to help engineers save time and improve chip performance.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Integrated circuits can be broadly classified into analog, digital and mixed-signal, consisting of analog and digital signaling on the same IC.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Digital integrated circuits can contain billions of logic gates, flip-flops, multiplexers, and other circuits in a few square millimeters.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] The small size of these circuits allows high speed, low power dissipation, and reduced manufacturing cost compared with board-level integration.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] These digital ICs, typically microprocessors, DSPs, and microcontrollers, use boolean algebra to process "one" and "zero" signals.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Among the most advanced integrated circuits are the microprocessors or "**cores**", used in personal computers, cell-phones, etc.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Several cores may be integrated together in a single IC or chip.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Digital memory chips and application-specific integrated circuits (ASICs) are examples of other families of integrated circuits.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] In the 1980s, programmable logic devices were developed.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] These devices contain circuits whose logical function and connectivity can be programmed by the user, rather than being fixed by the integrated circuit manufacturer.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] This allows a chip to be programmed to do various LSI-type functions such as logic gates, adders and registers.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Current FPGAs can (as of 2016) implement the equivalent of millions of gates and operate at frequencies up to 1 GHz.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Analog ICs, such as sensors, power management circuits, and operational amplifiers (op-amps), process continuous signals, and perform analog functions such as amplification, active filtering, demodulation, and mixing.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] ICs can combine analog and digital circuits on a chip to create functions such as analog-to-digital converters and digital-to-analog converters.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Such mixed-signal circuits offer smaller size and lower cost, but must account for signal interference.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Prior to the late 1990s, radios could not be fabricated in the same low-cost CMOS processes as microprocessors.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] But since 1998, radio chips have been developed using RF CMOS processes.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Examples include Intel's DECT cordless phone, or 802.11 (Wi-Fi) chips created by Atheros and other companies.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] The semiconductors of the periodic table of the chemical elements were identified as the most likely materials for a *solid-state vacuum tube*.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Starting with copper oxide, proceeding to germanium, then silicon, the materials were systematically studied in the 1940s and 1950s.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Today, monocrystalline silicon is the main substrate used for ICs although some III-V compounds of the periodic table such as gallium arsenide are used for specialized applications like LEDs, lasers, solar cells and the highest-speed integrated circuits.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] It took decades to perfect methods of creating crystals with minimal defects in semiconducting materials' crystal structure.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Semiconductor ICs are fabricated in a planar process which includes three key process steps – photolithography, deposition (such as chemical vapor deposition), and etching.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] The main process steps are supplemented by doping and cleaning.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] More recent or high-performance ICs may instead use multi-gate FinFET or GAAFET transistors instead of planar ones, starting at the 22 nm node (Intel) or 16/14 nm nodes.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Mono-crystal silicon wafers are used in most applications (or for special applications, other semiconductors such as gallium arsenide are used).
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Photolithography is used to mark different areas of the substrate to be doped or to have polysilicon, insulators or metal (typically aluminium or copper) tracks deposited on them.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Dopants are impurities intentionally introduced to a semiconductor to modulate its electronic properties.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Doping is the process of adding dopants to a semiconductor material.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Since a CMOS device only draws current on the *transition* between logic states, CMOS devices consume much less current than bipolar junction transistor devices.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Random-access memory (RAM) is the most regular type of integrated circuit; the highest-density ICs are therefore memories, although even a microprocessor typically includes on-chip memory.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] (See the regular array structure at the bottom of the first image.) Although device structures are highly intricate—with feature widths that have been shrinking for decades—the material layers remain much thinner than the lateral dimensions of the devices.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] These layers are fabricated using a process analogous to photolithography, but light in the visible spectrum cannot be used for patterning, as its wavelengths are too large.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Instead, ultraviolet (UV) photons of shorter wavelength are employed to expose each layer.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Because the features are so small, electron microscopes are essential tools for a process engineer working on fabrication process debugging.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Each device is tested before packaging using automated test equipment (ATE), in a procedure known as wafer testing or wafer probing.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] The wafer is then cut into rectangular blocks, each known as a *die*.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Each functional die (plural *dice*, *dies*, or *die*) is connected into a package using aluminium (or gold) bond wires, which are attached by thermosonic bonding.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Thermosonic bonding, first introduced by A.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Coucoulas, provided a reliable means of forming electrical connections between the die and the outside world.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] After packaging, devices undergo final testing on the same or similar ATE used during wafer probing.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] In addition, industrial CT scanning can be employed for inspection.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Test cost can account for over 25% of total fabrication cost for low-cost products, but is relatively negligible for low-yielding, larger, or higher-cost devices.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] As of 2022, a fabrication facility (commonly known as a *semiconductor fab*) can cost over US$12 billion to construct.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] The cost of a fabrication facility rises over time because of increased complexity of new products; this is known as Rock's law.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] ICs can be manufactured either in-house by integrated device manufacturers (IDMs) or using the foundry model.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] IDMs are vertically integrated companies (like Intel and Samsung) that design, manufacture and sell their own ICs, and may offer design and/or manufacturing (foundry) services to other companies (the latter often to fabless companies).
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] In the foundry model, fabless companies (like Nvidia) only design and sell ICs and outsource all manufacturing to pure play foundries such as TSMC.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] These foundries may offer IC design services.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] The earliest integrated circuits were packaged in ceramic flat packs, which continued to be used by the military for many years due to their reliability and compact size.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Commercial packaging rapidly shifted to the dual in-line package (DIP) – first in ceramic, later in plastic, typically a cresol–formaldehyde–novolac resin.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] In the 1980s, the pin count of VLSI circuits exceeded the practical limit of DIP packaging, leading to the adoption of pin grid array (PGA) and leadless chip carrier (LCC) packages.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Surface-mount technology (SMT) emerged in the early 1980s and gained popularity by the late 1980s, offering finer lead pitch and using leads formed as either gull-wing or J-lead.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] A common example is the small-outline integrated circuit (SOIC) package – which occupies about 30–50% less board area than an equivalent DIP and is typically 70% thinner – featuring gull-wing leads extending from its two long sides with a standard lead spacing of 0.050 inches.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] By the late 1990s, plastic quad flat pack (PQFP) and thin small-outline package (TSOP) designs became the most common for high pin-count devices, though PGA packages remain in use for high-performance microprocessors.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Ball grid array (BGA) packaging has existed since the 1970s.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] The flip-chip BGA (FCBGA), developed in the 1990s, enables much higher pin counts than most other package types.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] In an FCBGA, the die is mounted upside-down and connected to the package balls through a substrate similar to a printed circuit board, rather than by bonding wires.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] This design allows an array of input/output (I/O) connections – called Area-I/O – to be distributed across the entire die instead of being limited to its edges.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] While BGA devices eliminate the need for a dedicated socket, they are significantly more difficult to replace if they fail.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Intel transitioned away from PGA to land grid array (LGA) and BGA beginning in 2004, with the last PGA socket released in 2014 for mobile platforms.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] As of 2018, AMD uses PGA packages on mainstream desktop processors, BGA packages on mobile processors, and high-end desktop and server microprocessors use LGA packages.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Electrical signals leaving the die must pass through the material electrically connecting the die to the package, through the conductive traces (paths) in the package, through the leads connecting the package to the conductive traces on the printed circuit board.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] The materials and structures used in the path these electrical signals must travel have very different electrical properties, compared to those that travel to different parts of the same die.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] As a result, they require special design techniques to ensure the signals are not corrupted, and much more electric power than signals confined to the die itself.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] When multiple dies are put in one package, the result is a system in package, abbreviated SiP.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] A multi-chip module (MCM) is created by combining multiple dies on a small substrate often made of ceramic.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] The distinction between a large MCM and a small printed circuit board is sometimes fuzzy.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Packaged integrated circuits are usually large enough to include identifying information.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Four common sections are the manufacturer's name or logo, the part number, a part production batch number and serial number, and a four-digit date-code to identify when the chip was manufactured.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Extremely small surface-mount technology parts often bear only a number used in a manufacturer's lookup table to find the integrated circuit's characteristics.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] The manufacturing date is commonly represented as a two-digit year followed by a two-digit week code, such that a part bearing the code 8341 was manufactured in week 41 of 1983, or approximately in October 1983.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] The possibility of copying by photographing each layer of an integrated circuit and preparing photomasks for its production on the basis of the photographs obtained is a reason for the introduction of legislation for the protection of layout designs.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] The US Semiconductor Chip Protection Act of 1984 established intellectual property protection for photomasks used to produce integrated circuits.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] A diplomatic conference held at Washington, D.C., in 1989 adopted a Treaty on Intellectual Property in Respect of Integrated Circuits, also called the Washington Treaty or IPIC Treaty.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] The treaty is currently not in force, but was partially integrated into the TRIPS agreement.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] There are several United States patents connected to the integrated circuit, which include patents by J.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] National laws protecting IC layout designs have been adopted in a number of countries, including Japan, the EC, the UK, Australia, and Korea.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] The UK enacted the Copyright, Designs and Patents Act, 1988, c.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] 213, after it initially took the position that its copyright law fully protected chip topographies.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] See *British Leyland Motor Corp v Armstrong Patents Co*.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Criticisms of inadequacy of the UK copyright approach as perceived by the US chip industry are summarized in further chip rights developments.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Australia passed the Circuit Layouts Act 1989 as a *sui generis* form of chip protection.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Korea passed the *Act Concerning the Layout-Design of Semiconductor Integrated Circuits* in 1992.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] In the early days of simple integrated circuits, the technology's large scale limited each chip to only a few transistors, and the low degree of integration meant the design process was relatively simple.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Manufacturing yields were also quite low by today's standards.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] As metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) technology progressed, the size of individual transistors shrank rapidly.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] By the 1980s, millions of MOS transistors could be placed on one chip, and good designs required thorough planning, giving rise to the field of electronic design automation, or EDA.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Some SSI and MSI chips, like discrete transistors, are still mass-produced, both to maintain old equipment and build new devices that require only a few gates.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] The 7400 series of TTL chips, for example, has become a de facto standard and remains in production.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] The first integrated circuits contained only a few transistors.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Early digital circuits containing tens of transistors provided a few logic gates, and early linear ICs such as the Plessey SL201 or the Philips TAA320 had as few as two transistors.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] The number of transistors in an integrated circuit has increased dramatically since then.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] SSI circuits were crucial to early aerospace projects, and aerospace projects helped inspire development of the technology.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Both the Minuteman missile and Apollo program needed lightweight digital computers for their inertial guidance systems.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Although the Apollo Guidance Computer led and motivated integrated-circuit technology, it was the Minuteman missile that forced it into mass-production.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] The Minuteman missile program and various other United States Navy programs accounted for the total $4 million integrated circuit market in 1962, and by 1968, U.S.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Government spending on space and defense still accounted for 37% of the $312 million total production.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Government supported the nascent integrated circuit market until costs fell enough to allow IC firms to penetrate the industrial market and eventually the consumer market.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] The average price per integrated circuit dropped from $50 in 1962 to $2.33 in 1968.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Integrated circuits began to appear in consumer products by the turn of the 1970s decade.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] A typical application was FM inter-carrier sound processing in television receivers.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] The first application MOS chips were small-scale integration (SSI) chips.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Atalla's proposal of the MOS integrated circuit chip in 1960, the earliest experimental MOS chip to be fabricated was a 16-transistor chip built by Fred Heiman and Steven Hofstein at RCA in 1962.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] The first practical application of MOS SSI chips was for NASA satellites.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] The next step in the development of integrated circuits introduced devices which contained hundreds of transistors on each chip, called "medium-scale integration" (MSI).
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] MOSFET scaling technology made it possible to build high-density chips.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] In 1964, Frank Wanlass demonstrated a single-chip 16-bit shift register he designed, with a then-incredible 120 MOS transistors on a single chip.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] The same year, General Microelectronics introduced the first commercial MOS integrated circuit chip, consisting of 120 p-channel MOS transistors.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] It was a 20-bit shift register, developed by Robert Norman and Frank Wanlass.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] MOS chips further increased in complexity at a rate predicted by Moore's law, leading to chips with hundreds of MOSFETs on a chip by the late 1960s.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Further development, driven by the same MOSFET scaling technology and economic factors, led to "large-scale integration" (LSI) by the mid-1970s, with tens of thousands of transistors per chip.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] The masks used to process and manufacture SSI, MSI and early LSI and VLSI devices (such as the microprocessors of the early 1970s) were mostly created by hand, often using Rubylith-tape or similar.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Integrated circuits such as 1K-bit RAMs, calculator chips, and the first microprocessors, that began to be manufactured in moderate quantities in the early 1970s, had under 4,000 transistors.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] True LSI circuits, approaching 10,000 transistors, began to be produced around 1974, for computer main memories and second-generation microprocessors.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] "Very-large-scale integration" (VLSI) is a development that started with hundreds of thousands of transistors in the early 1980s.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] As of 2023, maximum transistor counts continue to grow beyond 5.3 trillion transistors per chip.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Multiple developments were required to achieve this increased density.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Manufacturers moved to smaller MOSFET design rules and cleaner fabrication facilities.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] The path of process improvements was summarized by the International Technology Roadmap for Semiconductors (ITRS), which has since been succeeded by the International Roadmap for Devices and Systems (IRDS).
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Electronic design tools improved, making it practical to finish designs in a reasonable time.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] The more energy-efficient CMOS replaced NMOS and PMOS, avoiding a prohibitive increase in power consumption.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] The complexity and density of modern VLSI devices made it no longer feasible to check the masks or do the original design by hand.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Instead, engineers use EDA tools to perform most functional verification work.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] In 1986, one-megabit random-access memory (RAM) chips were introduced, containing more than one million transistors.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Microprocessor chips passed the million-transistor mark in 1989, and the billion-transistor mark in 2005.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] The trend continues largely unabated, with chips introduced in 2007 containing tens of billions of memory transistors.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] To reflect the continuing increase in complexity, the term *ULSI* ("ultra-large-scale integration") was introduced for chips containing more than one million transistors.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Wafer-scale integration (WSI) is a technique for creating very large integrated circuits by using an entire silicon wafer to fabricate a single "super-chip".
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] By combining large size with reduced packaging, WSI offered the potential for significantly lower costs in certain applications, most notably massively parallel supercomputers.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] The term itself was derived from *Very-Large-Scale Integration* (VLSI), which represented the state of the art at the time WSI was under development.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] A system-on-a-chip (SoC or SOC) is an integrated circuit in which all the components needed for a computer or other system are included on a single chip.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] The design of such a device can be complex and costly, and whilst performance benefits can be had from integrating all needed components on one die, the cost of licensing and developing a one-die machine still outweigh having separate devices.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] With appropriate licensing, these drawbacks are offset by lower manufacturing and assembly costs and by a greatly reduced power budget: because signals among the components are kept on-die, much less power is required (see § Packaging).
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Further, signal sources and destinations are physically closer on die, reducing the length of wiring and therefore latency, transmission power costs and waste heat from communication between modules on the same chip.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] This has led to an exploration of so-called network-on-chip (NoC) devices, which apply system-on-chip design methodologies to digital communication networks as opposed to traditional bus architectures.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] A three-dimensional integrated circuit (3D-IC) has two or more layers of active electronic components that are integrated both vertically and horizontally into a single circuit.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Communication between layers uses on-die signaling, so power consumption is much lower than in equivalent separate circuits.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Judicious use of short vertical wires can substantially reduce overall wire length for faster operation.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] To allow identification during production, most silicon chips will have a serial number in one corner.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] It is also common to add the manufacturer's logo.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] Ever since ICs were created, some chip designers have used the silicon surface area for surreptitious, non-functional images or words.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] These artistic additions, often created with great attention to detail, showcase the designers' creativity and add a touch of personality to otherwise utilitarian components.
[src:integrated-circuit/integrated-circuit] These are sometimes referred to as chip art, silicon art, silicon graffiti or silicon doodling.
